er Peover, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1414–1477":"1414–1477","1416–Female":"1416–Deceased","1410–1498":"1410–1498","1430–1498":"1430–1498","1433–Male":"1433–Deceased","1388–1416":"1388–1416","1390–1414":"1390–1414","Abt 1433":"about 1433","1390":"1390","1414":"1414","Abt 1460":"about 1460","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1414 (19-29)":"1414","1388":"1388","1498":"1498","1410":"1410","about 1413":"about 1413","1430":"1430","1416":"1416","Beeston, Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of, BEESTON, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Lower Peover, Cheshire, England":"Lower Peover, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beeston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of the many places in England so called. Those in Nottinghamshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire were settlements where bent grass grew (Old English <i>bēos</i> ‘rough grass’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’). In Bedfordshire it probably denoted a settlement on a bend (Old English <i>byge</i> + genitive singular <i>-es</i> + <i>tūn</i>). The hamlet stands on a marked bend of the river Yvel. In Cheshire it is named from a rock, below which trading took place (Old English <i>byge</i> ‘commerce’ + Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’). The reference is to a prominent crag where the remains of Beeston Castle stand. Compare   Beaston   and   Beeson  .","occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived in that part of a village known in Middle English as <i>bi este toun</i> ‘(place) at the east (end) of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   and   Beaston  ."]},{"name":"Beeson","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston  , a habitational name from a place called Beeston. The spelling reflects the local pronunciation of the Nottinghamshire placename, although this form is now quite widespread in England."]},{"name":"Beaston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   (the more common form of the surname in England), a habitational name from any of various places called Beeston."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Beeston was born in 1414, in Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord William Beeston, was 26 and his mother, Clemence Mainwaring, was 24. He married Margaret VERNON about 1438. He died in 1477, in his hometown, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1414–1477":"1414–1477","1416–Female":"1416–Surnud","1410–1498":"1410–1498","1430–1498":"1430–1498","1433–Male":"1433–Surnud","1388–1416":"1388–1416","1390–1414":"1390–1414","Abt 1433":"umbes 1433","1390":"1390","1414":"1414","Abt 1460":"umbes 1460","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1414 (19-29)":"1414","1388":"1388","1498":"1498","1410":"1410","about 1413":"umbes 1413","1430":"1430","1416":"1416","Beeston, Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of, BEESTON, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Ch